#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-use-usb-devices.rst:194
#: d50ac8a5dc6147d282debdc77eb85669
msgid "Identifying controllers using the Qube Manager"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-use-usb-devices.rst:197
#: 73567a4e81584c44a968f5b97ba00ea6
msgid ""
"Using Qube Manager you can quickly determine the controllers on your "
"system and their BDF addresses, but not which controller a particular "
"device is attached to."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-use-usb-devices.rst:199
#: 2c1b8fe6c2684056a59019f896c82803
msgid ""
"Open the Qube Manager, then right click on one of the qubes and open the "
"settings. Go to the tab “Devices”. Here you should see your available "
"devices along with their BDF addresses. Look for the lines containing "
"“USB controller”. They should look something like: ``01:00.0 USB "
"controller: Name of manufacturer``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-use-usb-devices.rst:201
#: 040a6b04d0e642bdbb9b564d91d0278a
msgid "The first part is the BDF address, in this example: ``01:00.0``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-use-usb-devices.rst:203
#: 604c6c474b6d401fb8ef138f5ac432d1
msgid ""
"If, for example, you have 2 USB controllers in your system because you "
"added one you should see 2 such lines and you can probably guess which "
"controller is the one on the mainboard and which one you added. For "
"example, if you have a mainboard with an Intel chipset, it is possible "
"that all of the mainboard devices show as “Intel Corporation”, while the "
"added controller shows another manufacturer’s name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-use-usb-devices.rst:205
#: 5f35e64959ab4bfea7b98ace17f01c60
msgid ""
"Now you should be able to tell which is the BDF address of the mainboard "
"USB controller or the added USB controller."
msgstr ""

